Day 11 — Functions (Methods)

Until now, you wrote everything inside main().
That’s messy and not how real developers write code.

👉 Functions help you reuse code + organize logic

1. What is a Function?

A function (method in Java) is a block of code that performs a task.

Example 1
public class Test {
    public static void sayHello(){
        System.out.println("Hello Vishnu");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args){
        sayHello();
    }
}
Example 2
public class Test {
    public static void printNumbers(){
        for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++){
            System.out.println(i);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args){
        printNumbers();
    }
}
2. Function with Parameters

You can pass values to a function.

Example 1
public class Test {
    public static void add(int a, int b){
        System.out.println(a + b);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args){
        add(10, 20);
    }
}
Example 2
public class Test {
    public static void greet(String name){
        System.out.println("Hello " + name);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args){
        greet("Vishnu");
    }
}
3. Function with Return Value

Instead of printing, return the result.

Example 1
public class Test {
    public static int add(int a, int b){
        return a + b;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args){
        int result = add(5, 3);
        System.out.println(result);
    }
}
Example 2
public class Test {
    public static int square(int n){
        return n * n;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args){
        System.out.println(square(4));
    }
}
4. Why Functions Matter (Don’t ignore this)

Without functions:

Code becomes huge
Hard to debug
Repetition everywhere

With functions:

Clean code
Reusable logic
Easy debugging
5. Common Mistakes
Mistake 1 — Forgetting return
public static int add(int a, int b){
    a + b;   // WRONG
}
Mistake 2 — Calling function incorrectly
add;  // WRONG

Correct:

add(10, 20);
